	"notes": [
		{
			"id": "nA_spTkT7ogBH-XuS",
			"markdown": "Explorers venture into places that are unmapped, poorly understood, or outright hostile. Whether crossing oceans, charting hyperspace routes, leading jungle expeditions, surveying alien ruins, or scouting the frontier beyond civilization, Explorers specialize in surviving the unknown and bringing others safely through it. They combine navigation, adaptability, fieldcraft, and curiosity with the nerve to go farther than anyone else.\n\nThe Explorer is a highly flexible template built around movement, discovery, and environmental mastery. Navigation is its defining skill, but different combinations of Advantages and secondary skills can produce wilderness scouts, expedition leaders, archaeologists, naval navigators, survey spacers, and countless other varieties of adventurer. Explorers are rarely front-line combatants, but they are expected to endure hardship, adapt quickly, and solve problems far from safety or support. Explorers are also often the first representatives of their people to encounter new cultures, worlds, species, or phenomena, and many become diplomats, scouts, intermediaries, or agents of expansion as much as navigators.\n\nThe *Expedition Leader* is the captain, caravan master, pathfinder, colonial leader, or famous explorer responsible for guiding others through dangerous territory. Expedition Leaders balance authority, diplomacy, and practical survival skills, often serving as both organizer and symbol for the expedition itself. They emphasize Leadership, Diplomacy, Navigation, Geography, Survival, and Tactics, backed by Charisma, Intuition, Fearlessness, and Cultural Adaptability. Common disadvantages include Sense of Duty, Code of Honor, Overconfidence, Workaholic, or Stubbornness.\n\nThe *Survey Scout* is the frontier ranger, reconnaissance scout, hostile-environment surveyor, or military pathfinder who operates far ahead of civilization and often far ahead of support. Survey Scouts are expected to move quietly, endure hardship, recognize danger early, and survive hostile environments long enough to bring back useful information. They focus on Survival, Camouflage, Tracking, Cartography, Navigation, Hiking, and combat sidearms or rifles, supported by Outdoorsman, Danger Sense, Combat Reflexes, and Fit. Typical disadvantages include Loner, Xenophilia, Curious, Code of Honor (Professional or Soldier’s), or Overconfidence.\n\nThe *Field-Scholar* covers xenologists, natural philosophers, anthropologists, archaeologists, planetary researchers, and scientific expedition members driven to study the unknown firsthand. Field-Scholars often balance intellectual curiosity with the practical demands of dangerous expeditions, becoming translators, negotiators, and interpreters between civilizations as often as scientists. They emphasize Archaeology, Anthropology, Biology, Linguistics, Xenology, Photography, and Diplomacy, paired with Language Talent, Cultural Adaptability, Intuition, and Wild Talent. Their curiosity and dedication frequently produce disadvantages such as Curious, Obsession, Pacifism (Reluctant Killer), Honesty, Workaholic, or Xenophilia.\n\nThe *Voidfarer* is the deep-space scout, hyperspace navigator, scout-service veteran, or long-range reconnaissance spacer who spends more time between worlds than on them. Voidfarers must endure isolation, confinement, unfamiliar gravity, and the constant risk of disaster while remaining calm and functional far from rescue or reinforcement. They focus on Navigation (Space or Hyperspace), Piloting, Spacer, Vacc Suit, Electronics Operation, and Shiphandling, supported by Born Spacer, G-Experience, Fearlessness, and Absolute Direction. Common disadvantages include Space Sickness, Loner, Sense of Duty, Overconfidence, or Xenophilia.\n\nEven in campaigns that are not primarily space-focused, Explorers may benefit from spacer skills such as Vacc Suit, Spacer, Piloting, or Navigation (Space) if interplanetary or orbital travel is common. Conversely, dedicated Voidfarers should still consider traditional exploration skills like Survival, Diplomacy, Biology, or Area Knowledge — strange worlds are still worlds, no matter how you reach them.\n\nExplorers should think carefully about the kind of terrain or environment they expect to face most often. A single high Navigation specialty can define an entire career, while broad secondary skills determine how well the Explorer survives once the journey begins."
		}
	]
